school children. The government's interpretation of the commerce clause is that children will contribute to the future economies, and it is therefore within the power of the government to regulate their education. It is notable that this argument was once used, without success, to ban guns from school grounds. &#10;2) The Necessary and Proper Clause. The N&amp;P stipulates that the government has the ability to enact legislation that is deemed necessary and proper to fulfilling its obligations. The government then deems 'general welfare' as part of its obligations, makes the leap that children are part of the benefactors of this 'general welfare', and starts writing laws. &#10;3) The 14th Amendment. Since the 14th Amendment allows the Bill of Rights to be 'incorporated' (see incorporation theory) into the states, then the 1st Amendment applies to the states. They are bound to follow the Constitution as much as the Federal government is. &#10;Another argument lies in funding. The government does have the power to allocate or deny federal funds. If states want federal funds, they'll do the federal government's 'suggestions'. This is how alcohol remains illegal to those under 21 (instead of 18): noone would dare write a law against the government's because they're afraid of losing funding. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1595" language="en" documentId="1859" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Angry Citizen" date="16th March 2011 07:58 PM" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://www.volconvo.com/forums/showthread.php?t=34286&amp;page=1" topic="prayer-in-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1859" notes="" title="Prayer in Public Schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="207"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="208" end="615"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="616" end="976"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="977" end="1242"